    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Rewriting the Election</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mavis Cain letter endorses Feb 12 editorial defending media's right to use exit-poll projections and suggests that those projections in Florida reflected voters' intentions more accurately than the certified vote count did</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Meddling With the News'' (editorial, Feb. 12):</p>
        <p>Your editorial rightly says that government ''should not try to intimidate or pressure the media'' and that the use of exit-poll projections ''should be up to journalists, not members of Congress.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Meddling With the News'' (editorial, Feb. 12):</p>
        <p>Your editorial rightly says that government ''should not try to intimidate or pressure the media'' and that the use of exit-poll projections ''should be up to journalists, not members of Congress.''</p>
        <p>Yes, indeed. The First Amendment is sacred.</p>
        <p>As for the ''scorching self-criticism'' of some of the networks, why this mea culpa? Consider the exit polls in Florida. They were based on questions posed to many who believed that they had voted for Al Gore. Possibly, the projections of a Democratic victory were more accurate than the declared result.</p>
        <p>MAVIS CAIN  Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., Feb. 13, 2001</p>
      </block>
